crowdsourced_yara_results.description: Detects ransomware exploiting and encrypting ESXi servers
crowdsourced_yara_results.author: Florian Roth

attributes.magic: ELF 64-bit LSB executable, x86-64, version 1 (SYSV), dynamically linked, interpreter /lib64/ld-linux-x86-64.so.2, for GNU/Linux 2.6.8, with debug_info, not stripped

threat_severity.level_description: Severity HIGH because it was considered ransomware. Other contributing factors were that it has known exploits and it could not be run in sandboxes.

crowdsourced_ai_results.analysis: The sample is a high-performance Linux ransomware encryptor, characteristic of variants targeting ESXi and large-scale storage environments (e.g., Babuk or HelloKitty/Hive derivatives). It utilizes the SOSEMANUK stream cipher for fast data encryption and RSA (OpenSSL) for session key protection. The binary dynamically resolves OpenSSL symbols via dlopen/dlsym to avoid static linkage detection. Notably, it supports intermittent encryption parameters (enc_step and enc_size), allowing it to skip portions of files to increase encryption speed while still rendering the data unrecoverablea hallmark of modern ransomware. Relevant IOCs include the use of the SOSEMANUK cipher, dynamic loading of 'libssl.so', and the file modification pattern of appending encrypted key material to the end of the target file.
